  "risks": [
    "The front-door recovery architecture is implemented for the repo-owned executable proof surface, but this is still not a broad public interop or product-support claim.",
    "If ACK, transport-parameter, and recovery evidence are not kept separate, the loss-detection proof surface will become harder to audit."
  ],
  "design_summary": "The repository-owned RFC 9002 recovery and congestion-control surface is now implemented for the current traced executable floor. The proof boundary remains explicit: ACK-frame, transport-parameter, RTT, congestion-control, PTO, sender/recovery ledger, packet-number-space cleanup, and benchmark evidence are linked through the RFC 9002 requirement homes and split artifacts.\nFuture recovery work must continue under a named gap or requirement slice, such as path migration, hosted interop widening, public-surface support, or newly discovered recovery behavior, rather than reopening this front-door artifact as an implicit umbrella.",
  "title": "QUIC RFC 9002 Loss-Detection Architecture",
